the new rhetoric held enormous appeal for those women who would appear to be its greatest targets: wealthy, fashionable 'women of quality'. Using the correspondence and diaries of these women, Tague traces the ways in which they adopted, adapted, and exploited ideals of femininity. In their hands, feminine values could become powerful tools that enabled them to compete for status and reputation. Ironically, by identifying femininity with private, trivial concerns, these ideals created unique opportunities for elite women. Female participation in informal social and political activities placed women at the heart of aristocratic power in the early eighteenth century, even as they employed the language of wifely subordination and domesticity. Ingrid Tague is Assistant Professor of History at the University of Denver.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFemininityxEnglandxHistory, 18th century. 0aFemininityzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aWomenxEnglandxSocial conditions, 18th century. 0aWomenxEnglandxSocial life and customs, 18th century. 0aWomenzEnglandxSocial conditionsy18th century. 0aWomenzEnglandxSocial life and customsy18th century. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh  afeminism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615178140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846151781423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846151781/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles